"Halley J.M.","Using models with long-term persistence to interpret the rapid increase of Earth's temperature",2009,"Physica A: Statistical Mechanics and its Applications","388","12",,"2492","2502",,,10.1016/j.physa.2009.02.027,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-63749087115&partnerID=40&md5=4ba82062a62d6239a1d80df71fc912a4","Department of Biological Applications and Technology, University of Ioannina, Ioannina, Greece","Halley, J.M., Department of Biological Applications and Technology, University of Ioannina, Ioannina, Greece","Statistical processes with long-term persistence (LTP) offer a promising approach to modeling the natural dynamics of Earth's temperature. One such process, the family of 1 / f-noises, is used here to assess the plausibility of a natural origin for recent global warming. Following earlier studies, a model of natural variability with LTP is parameterized via paleoclimate reconstructions. The method developed here resolves a number of limitations in existing studies, primarily the problem of inaccuracies in estimating the spectral exponent of LTP. The output of the model is compared with the observed rate of temperature rise (0.61 {ring operator}C/century between 1850 and 2007 for Northern hemispheric land air temperatures). We find that rates comparable with the observed global warming are very rarely generated by the model of natural variability (the probability is less than 2.3×10-4). Thus, natural agencies are not a plausible explanation for the observed global warming unless all the paleoclimate reconstructions through which the model is parameterized are underestimating natural variance by a factor of at least four. © 2009 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Climate change; Long-term persistence","Climatology; Probability density function; Restoration; Air temperatures; Earth's temperatures; Long-term persistence; Natural dynamics; Natural variabilities; Paleoclimate reconstruction; Parameterized; Statistical process; Temperature rise; Global warming",,,,,,"Hegerl, G.C., (2007) Climate Change 2007: The Physical Science Basis. Contribution of Working Group I to the Fourth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, , Solomon S., et al. (Ed), Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, United Kingdom, New York, NY, USA; Hansen, J., (2006) Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America, 103, p. 14288; Govindan, R.B., (2002) Physical Review Letters, 89. , 028501-4; Koutsoyiannis, D., Efstratiadis, A., Mamassis, N., Christofides, A., (2008) Hydrological Sciences Journal/Journal Des Sciences Hydrologiques, 53, p. 671; Solow, A.R., (1987) Journal of Climate and Applied Meteorolgy, 26, p. 1401; Tsonis, A.A., Elsner, J.B., (1989) Geophysical Research Letters, 16, p. 795; Bloomfield, P., Nychka, D., (1992) Climatic Change, 21, p. 275; Galbraith, J.W., Green, C., (1992) Climatic Change, 22, p. 209; Woodward, W.A., Gray, H.L., (1993) Journal of Climate, 6, p. 953; Cohn, T.A., Lins, H.F., (2005) Geophysical Research Letters, 32. , art. no. L23402; Rybski, D., Bunde, A., Havlin, S., von Storch, H., (2006) Geophysical Research Letters, 33. , art. no. L06718; E.J. Wegman, D.W. Scott, Y.H. Said, U.S. Comm. on Energy and Commerce 2006Koutsoyiannis, D., Montanari, A., (2007) Water Resources Research, 43. , art. no. W05429; Taqqu, M.S., Teverovsky, V., Willinger, W., (1995) Fractals-an Interdisciplinary Journal on the Complex Geometry of Nature, 3, p. 785; Cannon, M.J., (1997) Physica A, 241, p. 606; Koscielny-Bunde, E., (1998) Physical Review Letters, 81, p. 729; Koutsoyiannis, D., (2003) Hydrological Sciences Journal-Journal Des Sciences Hydrologiques, 48, p. 3; Havlin, S., (1999) Physica A, 273, p. 46; Hurst, H.E., (1951) Transactions of the American Society of Civil Engineers, 116, p. 770; Klemes, V., (1974) Water Resources Research, 10, p. 675; Mandelbrot, B.B., Wallis, J.R., (1969) Water Resources Research, 5, p. 321; Wornell, G.W., (1993) Pro